03794nam a22006015i 9780292796812DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927968127 a10.7560/7069892doi  a(DE-B1597)587193  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPQ8179.S5bD413 2005eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a863/.642221 aSilva, José Asunción, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter-Dinner Conversation :bThe Diary of a Decadent /cJosé Asunción Silva. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tTRANSLATOR’S INTRODUCTION -- t“AN ART BOTH NERVOUS AND NEW” -- tAfter-Dinner Conversation TRANSLATION OF De sobremesa -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLost in a shipwreck in 1895, rewritten before the author's suicide in 1896, and not published until 1925, José Asunción Silva's After-Dinner Conversation (De sobremesa) is one of Latin America's finest fin de siècle novels and the first one to be translated into English. Perhaps the single best work for understanding turn-of-the-twentieth-century writing in South America, After-Dinner Conversation is also cited as the continent's first psychological novel and an outstanding example of modernista fiction and the Decadent sensibility. Semi-autobiographical and more important for style than plot, After-Dinner Conversation is the diary of a Decadent sensation-collector in exile in Paris who undertakes a quest to find his beloved Helen, a vision whom his fevered imagination sees as his salvation. Along the way, he struggles with irreconcilable urges and temptations that pull him in every direction while he endures an environment indifferent or hostile to spiritual and intellectual pursuits, as did the modernista writers themselves. Kelly Washbourne's excellent translation preserves Silva's lush prose and experimental style. In the introduction, one of the most wide-ranging in Silva criticism, Washbourne places the life and work of Silva in their literary and historical contexts, including an extended discussion of how After-Dinner Conversation fits within Spanish American modernismo and the Decadent movement. Washbourne's perceptive comments and notes also make the novel accessible to general readers, who will find the work surprisingly fresh more than a century after its composition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aWashbourne, Kelly.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796812/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK